nRead also\n\nNick Mudimba: Details of journalist\'s daughter, expectant wife, emerge\n\nHe commended the late man\'s fighting spirit while in the hospital and asked Carol, the widow, to take heart since she has joined the league of people God fights for.\n\nRead also\n\n\"Nilikuwa tu 10 years\": Viral AFC Leopards fan opens up on how he lost his leg\n\nThe preacher called Carol to the dais and prayed for her with other religious leaders.\n\nAfter the prayers, tears were seen running down her cheeks.\n\nWhile viewing the body, she was inconsolable, and a mourner comforted her. In another video while walking to the hearse, mourners supported her to the car.\n\nRead also\n\nFlorence Robert’s husband speaks after remarrying, shares lovely photos with new wife\n\nShe was seen painfully weeping.\n\nKenyans took to social media to console the grief-stricken widow, and below are their messages:\n\nMarion Smith:\n\nOle Josei Osiagi:\n\nOrdah Amwayi:\n\nLily Malesi:\n\nJohny Atang\'a:\n\nJoan On Gayatri:\n\nSarah Ongele:\n\nDaniel Mpiding\n\nIn other news, the opposition leader was heartbroken by the demise of his aide.\n\nHe penned a touching tribute, comforting his family, describing him as a pillar of strength and the epitome of professionalism.\n\nRead also\n\nKenyan man writes Karen Nyamu love letter, shares why he\'s smitten with her\n\nSilas Jakakimba said that Raila cried on the phone after his aide\'s death.\n\nCaren Nyota, Head of Entertainment desk, contributed to this article adding messages of Kenyans comforting George Oduor\'s widow and other top trending stories.\n\nProofreading by Jackson Otukho, copy editor at TUKO.co.ke.\n\nSource: TUKO.co.ke\n\nPatricia Tonui (Entertainment editor) Patricia Tonui is a journalist and an entertainment editor at TUKO.co.ke. She was a Broadcast Journalism student at The University of Nairobi class of 2022 and has a 2-year experience working in digital media having previously worked at mpasho.co.ke. Patricia joined Tuko.co.ke in 2022. Reach out to patricia.tunoi@tuko.co.ke if you have entertaining, and informative news to share.\n\nJackson Otukho (Copyeditor) Jackson Otukho is a multi-media journalist and current affairs editor at TUKO.co.ke. In 2019, he graduated with a Bachelor of Science degree in Media Science from Moi University. He has over seven years of experience in digital and print media. He initially worked as a news editor at Standard Media Group (2014-2017) and Citizen TV (2019 May- 2019 September). Through his career, he has won several awards, including the editor with the cleanest copy and with the most social media engagement. Mail: jackson.otukho@tuko.co.ke','News','2025-04-05 07:22:44','2025-04-05 07:22:44',NULL),(15,'https://www.tuko.co.ke/entertainment/celebrities/584544-nick-mudimba-journalist-leaves-daughter-expectant-wife/','Nick Mudimba: Journalist Leaves Behind Daughter, Expectant Wife','2003-04-25 00:00:00','Tuko','CHECK OUT: Don\'t let unemployment hold you back. Start your digital marketing journey today.\n\nNick Mudimba will be laid to rest on Saturday, April 5, in Gem, Siaya county.\n\nThe 37-year-old renowned journalist passed away on March 23 at his Syokimau home.\n\nPAY ATTENTION: TUKO is in WhatsApp Channels now! Subscribe and read news in favourite messenger.\n\nMudimba\'s memorial mass was held on April 3 at the Holy Family Basilica in Nairobi.\n\nFamily, friends and colleagues of the deceased journalist attended the requiem mass, and those who had a chance to speak paid glowing tributes to him.\n\nRead also\n\nGeorge Oduor: Widow of Raila Odinga\'s bodyguard painfully weeps during hubby\'s memorial mass\n\nThe MC of the event revealed that Mudimba has left behind a heavily pregnant wife who is due this month and a nine-year-old daughter.\n\nMudimba\'s wife penned a touching tribute to him, noting that losing him is the hardest thing that has ever happened to her.\n\nShe recalled the moments Mudimba would feel their unborn child and pray for its protection.\n\nRead also\n\nNick Mudimba’s boss breaks down while reading tribute during journalist\'s mass\n\nThe grief-stricken widow described her husband as her best friend, confidant and romantic gentleman, reminiscing about how he would drop her off at work and take her back home.\n\nRead also\n\nJalang\'o honours Nick Mudimba with emotional tribute: \"It\'s God\'s will\"\n\nLang\'ata MP Jalang\'o paid an emotional tribute to the seasoned journalist during his requiem mass.\n\nJalang\'o showered his close friend with love, describing him as a true friend. The politician also reflected on their shared dreams.\n\nThe former radio presenter talked about how most of the people from their village are doctors and lawyers, and they (he and Mudimba) had vowed to match their village mates.\n\nJalang\'o admitted his friend\'s death hit him the hardest.\n\nThe CGTN journalist\'s body leaves Nairobi on April 4, at 6am, accompanied by his family.\n\nThe cortege will leave Kisumu International Airport at 9am for his home in Luanda Dudi, Siaya county.\n\nThe body will then arrive at his final resting place for an overnight prayer and vigil.\n\nOn Saturday, April 5, the body will leave home for Luanda Dudi Secondary School for a funeral service.\n\nRead also\n\nFlorence Robert’s husband speaks after remarrying, shares lovely photos with new wife\n\nThe funeral service will begin at 9.30am and mourners will be allowed to view the body from 9:35am.\n\nMudimba worked for KTN, Switch TV, Supersport, Bamba Sport and CGTN, where he worked until his untimely demise.\n\nThe journalist\'s last assignment was in Addis Ababa, covering the AUC chairman elections.\n\nMudimba was born on November 19, 1987, in Busia.\n\nApart from being a journalist, Mudimba was also chasing his flying passion and was working towards his pilot\'s license.\n\nCaren Nyota, Head of Entertainment desk, contributed to this article adding details of Mudimba\'s final journey\n\nProofreading by Mercy Nyambura, copy editor at TUKO.co.ke.\n\nSource: TUKO.co.ke\n\nCaren Nyota (Entertainment editor) Caren Nyota is the Head of Entertainment Desk at TUKO.co.ke with 10 years of experience in print and digital media. She holds a Bachelor\'s Degree in Journalism & Mass Communication from The University of Nairobi. Previously worked as an editor at Mpasho.co.ke, The Star Kenya and as Features/Investigative Reporter at Radio Africa Group. Have an extraordinary story to share with Caren? Email: Caren.nyota@tuko.co.ke.\n\nMercy Nyambura (Copyeditor)','News','2025-04-05 07:22:53','2025-04-05 07:22:53',NULL),(16,'https://www.tuko.co.ke/business-economy/584712-vital-european-defence-startups-facing-hurdles/','Vital European defence startups still facing hurdles','2005-04-25 00:00:00','Tuko','PAY ATTENTION: Flexible Payment Plans Available! Invest in Yourself & See the Return with Our Affordable Copywriting Course!\n\nOpportunities and investment have surged for European defence startups since Russia\'s invasion of Ukraine, industry players say, with shifts by governments and investors shaking up a sector long a byword for ponderous development.\n\nResearch published in February by the NATO Innovation Fund (NIF) and market analytics firm Dealroom found that venture capital going into European \"defence, security and resilience\" startups leapt 30 percent in the two years to 2024, reaching $5.2 billion.\n\nThat reflected a shift already under way before Russia\'s full-scale assault in early 2022 as \"underlying technologies\" began to be adapted for battlefield use, NIF partner Patrick Schneider-Sikorsky told AFP.\n\nHe named \"additive manufacturing, AI, RF (radio frequency) technologies, battery technologies\" as ingredients already attracting investment before \"sheer necessity\" supercharged their use and evolution on Ukrainian battlefields.\n\nBut the urgent need to develop state-of-the-art battlefield tech -- a constantly moving target in the crucible of Ukraine -- continues to run into hurdles.\n\nRead also\n\nTrump goads China after Beijing retaliates in global trade war\n\nAmong the most stubborn is getting investors -- from sovereign wealth funds and public banks to pension funds or family offices of wealthy individuals -- to pump cash into defence, which is often lumped in with \"sin stocks\".\n\nPAY ATTENTION: TUKO is in WhatsApp Channels now! Subscribe and read news in favourite messenger.\n\nOne company that has run into this problem is German startup Donaustahl, which has rapidly evolved from making accessories for sports pistol shooting to developing armed drones.\n\nAlthough it attracted widespread interest at last year\'s Berlin air and space trade fair, \"Donaustahl, as a weapons company, has just been shut out from financing and the capital markets so far,\" founder Stefan Thumann told AFP.\n\nIt was \"just like gambling and drugs\", he complained.\n\nWhile Thumann said he is now in talks with prospective investors, he also took the rare step of going directly to fans of his company, and via a social media presence, to raise cash by issuing digital bonds.\n\nRead also\n\nGerman industry grapples with AI at trade fair\n\nGetting around restrictions on defence or so-called \"dual-use\" technologies -- those with both civilian and military applications -- would require revising existing agreements on how funds can deploy investors\' cash, or setting up altogether new funds, NIF\'s Schneider-Sikorsky said.\n\nThere have been some signs of movement from public institutions.\n\nThe European Investment Bank agreed last year to remove a requirement that \"dual-use\" companies it finances make at least 50 percent of revenue from civilian customers.\n\nLooking from east to west among European governments, \"you do see this very distinct gradient of appetites from more offensive things to more defensive things, from a tech perspective,\" said Jack Wang, UK managing director for venture capital company Project A.\n\nFor instance, Russia-neighbouring Estonia last year announced the creation of a 50-million-euro ($54.1 million) fund to invest in both defence and dual-use tech.\n\nPia Santavirta, chief executive of Finland\'s public investment fund Tesi, last month named \"defence tech\" among \"future growth sectors\" it was eyeing.\n\nRead also\n\nDeutsche Bank asset manager DWS fined 25 mn euros for \'greenwashing\'\n\nAnd private investors are scenting opportunity from the hundreds of billions in potential spending trailed especially by Berlin and Brussels in recent weeks, with Germany amending its constitution to enable more borrowing to fund defence.\n\nOn the other end of the chain from investment is the end customer, where defence startups are confronted with military procurement systems used to taking years over deals.\n\n\"Most VC (venture capital) funds have got used to investing in software to sell to small businesses or consumers,\" Project A\'s Wang said, expecting their backing to \"convert to revenue... within one-and-a-half, two years\".\n\n\"The military sales cycle doesn\'t operate like that\".\n\n\"Both cultures are going to have to change,\" said NIF\'s Schneider-Sikorsky.\n\nDefence ministries may in future \"have a defence tech company that is almost on contract with the military to produce and continuously upgrade capabilities, as opposed to just selling a bit of hardware that\'s going to be stockpiled,\" he added.\n\nRead also\n\n\'Give me a break\': Trump tariffs threaten Japan auto sector\n\n\"Some countries just need to get away from their specific gold-trimmed solutions,\" Donaustahl chief Thumann urged.\n\n\"We don\'t have the time... I hope the German army will modernise its procurement system and do away with some super-complicated hurdles in tendering that leave small firms out in the cold.\"\n\nSource: AFP\n\nAFP AFP text, photo, graphic, audio or video material shall not be published, broadcast, rewritten for broadcast or publication or redistributed directly or indirectly in any medium. AFP news material may not be stored in whole or in part in a computer or otherwise except for personal and non-commercial use. AFP will not be held liable for any delays, inaccuracies, errors or omissions in any AFP news material or in transmission or delivery of all or any part thereof or for any damages whatsoever. As a newswire service, AFP does not obtain releases from subjects, individuals, groups or entities contained in its photographs, videos, graphics or quoted in its texts. Further, no clearance is obtained from the owners of any trademarks or copyrighted materials whose marks and materials are included in AFP material. Therefore you will be solely responsible for obtaining any and all necessary releases from whatever individuals and/or entities necessary for any uses of AFP material.','News','2025-04-05 07:23:02','2025-04-05 07:23:02',NULL),(17,'https://www.tuko.co.ke/facts-lifehacks/fashion-style/583616-what-rarest-hair-type-quick-facts-type-1a-hair/','What is the rarest hair type? Quick facts about Type 1A hair','2004-04-25 00:00:00','Tuko','What is the rarest hair type? Type 1A hair is the least common, known for its straight strands, fine texture, and smooth appearance. While genetic makeup primarily affects an individual\'s hair type, other factors like environmental conditions play a part. So, what do you need to know about type 1A hair?\n\nWhat is the rarest hair type in the world? According to research and hair experts, type 1A hair is the rarest of all hair types across the global population. This unique hair type has no curls and requires special care. 1A hair is common among women of Asian descent. Here are some quick facts about this hair:\n\nRead also\n\n15 black celebrities with curly hair who look great in 2021\n\nType 1A is the straightest among the three type 1 hair types. It is pin-straight, flat, and fine, with a feathery appearance. Type 1B is straight with minimal volume and body, while 1C is straight but thick, with considerable volume.\n\n1A hair strands are straight and do not curl even when wet, making it difficult to hold the hair in styles that require volume. The light strands make it prone to breakage. Women with type 1A hair are advised to get short, blunt haircuts to increase the hair volume and the appearance of thickness.\n\nOne of the most notable traits of type 1A hair is its oiliness caused by the natural hair oil freely moving up and down the straight follicles. For this reason, this hair type requires frequent shampooing using dry shampoos to control the oiliness.\n\nRead also\n\nList of black hair types and how to identify them (pictures)\n\nType 1A hair has a smooth sheen that gives it a striking appearance due to the production of natural hair oils. The oils keep the hair moisturized and resilient to other forms of damage. Compared to other hair types, 1A grows relatively fast.\n\nType 1A hair can be flat and plain, restricting individuals from exploring different hairstyles. Additionally, the natural production of sebum can make it greasy. Here are some tips on how to manage this hair type:\n\nRead also\n\nWhat is the difference between 3c and 4a hair?\n\nAccording to Vogue, an estimated 60% of the global population has naturally curly hair. The prevalence varies across ethnicity and background. Curly hair is found primarily among African natives although it is also found in the European, Middle Eastern, South Asian, and Latin American regions.\n\nNo. Type 2A hair is common among people of Caucasian descent and a few of mixed heritage. It is flat for a few inches from the root, gaining volume and body towards the end of the strands. The naturally loose waves have an \'S\' shape. Type 2A hair has a fine to medium texture that is easy to manage and style. The curls can be straightened using heat styling or enhanced using holding products.\n\nRead also\n\n15 must-have African hair accessories for black women\n\nWhat is the rarest hair type? Type 1A is the least common hair type, but is unique for its silky, straight appearance. Once you understand how to take care of it and establish the right routine, you will enjoy the beauty of this hair and how to style it for whichever occasion.\n\nHow do you style natural hair? Tuko.co.ke published an article listing numerous ways you can rock your natural hair for any occasion. Hairstyles express your creativity and personality, allowing you to stand out wherever you go.\n\nIf you like your hair braided, the flat twists updo or box braids are excellent options. For ladies with short hair, some alternatives include the natural tapered cut or mini twists. Check out more options in the article.\n\nSource: TUKO.co.ke\n\nGrace Waruguru (Lifestyle editor) Grace Waruguru is a lifestyle reporter and holds a Bachelor\'s degree in Communication (Public Relations) from Daystar University, Kenya (Class of 2010). She has over 4 years of experience in article writing and digital media content creation for various local and global brands. Currently based in Nairobi, Kenya, Grace started working at Tuko.co.ke in October 2020 and as a content creator at Brand2D (June 2022 - May 2023). In 2023, Grace finished the AFP course on Digital Investigation Techniques. Email: Wagachuhi@gmail.com','News','2025-04-05 07:23:12','2025-04-05 07:23:12',NULL),(18,'https://www.tuko.co.ke/business-economy/584561-kcb-bank-announces-job-openings-kenyans-april/','KCB Bank Announces Several Managerial Job Openings for Kenyans in April','2003-04-25 00:00:00','Tuko','PAY ATTENTION: Flexible Payment Plans Available! Invest in Yourself & See the Return with Our Affordable Copywriting Course!\n\nTUKO.co.ke journalist Wycliffe Musalia has over six years of experience in financial, business, technology, climate and health reporting, which offers deep insights into Kenyan and global economic trends.\n\nKenya Commercial Bank (KCB) has invited applications for several job vacancies in April 2025.\n\nThe lender, which employs more than 9,00